{"author":"Joe Oakhart","data":{"fields":{"description":"## What\n\nCreate `examples/claude-skills/shared/test-design.md` — the shared TDD test-design standard — and wire it into the three skills at the point each incorporates testing. Written in the skills' voice, with the 'scale ceremony to the bug' principle explicit.\n\nA `shared/` directory is used rather than per-skill copies because the content is identical across all three skills and per-skill copies would silently diverge; the portability cost of the cross-directory reference is mitigated by an explicit README note (copying a single skill requires copying `shared/` alongside it) and by each SKILL.md naming the path relative to its own directory (`../shared/test-design.md`) plus its repo location, so the reference resolves both in this repo and in a skills installation where `shared/` sits beside the skill directories.\n\nThe shared file covers:\n- Existing-coverage inventory before authoring: the required artifact is a RED oracle, which may be an existing failing test, an existing test strengthened into RED form, or a new test only when nothing covers the behavior. Search by contract wording, public entry point, implementation symbol, error text, and bug/regression identifier; read the nearest tests.\n- A test contract card frozen before test code, with scaled fields: contract + citation, bug-triggering preconditions, production path, tier + why lower is insufficient, observable postcondition, CI gate are always required; negative control, collateral invariants, recovery, fault injection apply conditionally (stateful/atomicity/concurrency work).\n- Test-tier selection rule: the smallest tier that still crosses every component in the proven mechanism, with the bug-class -> tier table (unit / producer-consumer contract / real CLI subprocess / real git repos / multi-process with deterministic barrier / parent-child subprocess / kill-and-restart crash recovery / stateful verified fake / behavioral eval). Work spanning several bug classes takes the tier per mechanism-component; at planning time, when the mechanism is not yet known, the acceptance criteria name the observable oracle and defer tier choice to implementation.\n- 'Trigger the mechanism, assert the contract': arrange conditions that force the mechanism through the smallest production path crossing the faulty seam; assert the public/contractual consequence, never mock call counts, private helpers, intermediate payloads, or source text.\n- Minimum behavioral oracle: prove the fixture preconditions; assert an exact behavioral postcondition (not is-not-None / nonempty / no-exception); collateral invariants for stateful operations; a clean retry where the contract is atomicity/recoverability.\n- Contrast case: default for input-class defects and stateful operations (nearest passing control / second representative input, parameterized where a family applies); justified omission allowed for trivially single-point bugs.\n- Fault realism: the injected fault must occur inside the code whose recovery/cleanup is under test (fail the real second rename, not a top-level wrapper); race tests must synchronize with a barrier/pipe/marker/failpoint, never timing-only sleeps as the primary mechanism.\n- Prove the test gates: the runner collects the node; it runs (not SKIP/XFAIL) in the supported CI environment; any temporary xfail is strict=True with a removal condition; the test runs under a gating CI command.\n- Defect-seeded mutation: derive the mutation from the confirmed root cause (re-introduce the exact defect), not an arbitrary negation.\n- LLM-surface evals: pinned model/settings, paired before/after prompts, multiple samples with a predeclared threshold and reported failure rates, plus a negative control — quantified rates, never one RED and one GREEN sample.\n\nSkill integration (each SKILL.md references `../shared/test-design.md` relative to its own directory, also naming the repo path `examples/claude-skills/shared/test-design.md`):\n- `examples/claude-skills/rebar-debug/SKILL.md`: Step 4 becomes 'Design and prove a RED oracle' — inventory first, contract card, tier rule, then RED with proven preconditions, loading the shared file at Phase 2 entry. Step 4's existing LLM-surface paragraph is updated to cite the shared file's quantified-eval requirements as the governing RED-artifact standard, superseding its current single-eval description. Step 5's mutation check becomes defect-seeded, and the fixer handoff list gains a fourth item — the frozen contract card (intended postcondition + invariants) — appended after 'confirmed root cause, evidence, original reproduction steps', while test fixture/assertions stay held out.\n- `examples/claude-skills/rebar-implement/SKILL.md`: Phase 4a/4b reference the shared file for oracle design (inventory, tier, oracle completeness, gating proof); held-out structure unchanged.\n- `examples/claude-skills/rebar-brainstorm/SKILL.md`: in the existing 'Before recording tickets, read the project's plan-review gate' section, add: before recording any ticket whose acceptance criteria will include or reference testing, verification, or behavioral oracles, read the shared file — when in doubt, read it (the cost is one file read; the benefit is correctly-shaped ACs that name the observable oracle).\n- `examples/claude-skills/README.md`: document the shared/ directory convention (copying a single skill requires copying shared/ alongside it).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `examples/claude-skills/shared/test-design.md` exists and covers every bullet above (inventory, contract card, tier table + multi-tier/planning-time rule, trigger/assert rule, oracle minimum, contrast default, fault realism, gating proof, defect-seeded mutation, LLM evals) with the scale-to-the-bug principle stated.\n- [ ] `grep -l 'shared/test-design.md' examples/claude-skills/rebar-debug/SKILL.md examples/claude-skills/rebar-implement/SKILL.md examples/claude-skills/rebar-brainstorm/SKILL.md` lists all three files, each reference sitting at the integration point named above.\n- [ ] rebar-debug's Step 4 is retitled to RED-oracle design, its LLM-surface paragraph defers to the shared eval standard, and Step 5 hands the fixer the contract card as a fourth handoff item without exposing held-out test code.\n- [ ] `examples/claude-skills/README.md` documents the shared/ convention including the copy-alongside note.\n- [ ] `make lint` passes (repo hygiene; the content gate is the grep AC above plus the recorded verify commands)."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783885166897377001,"uuid":"4a4e54ff-f2a4-47cb-8171-bea4f2add446"}